body:
I am using React ver 15.6.x and  have created my React JS components using ES6 style class patterns and I am not using 'React.createClass' anywhere in my app.  Still on my client side node server, I am getting deprecation warning like shown as below screen-shot : 
<img width="1410" alt="screen shot 2018-05-15 at 18 24 44" src="https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/16350637/40057941-4dcb404c-586d-11e8-91a4-f2e8a3689051.png">

Below is my React component code as per ES6 class style, DO I NEED to worry about this warning, or what should I do because I have created my React component as per standard guideline mentioned on this link https://reactjs.org/blog/2017/04/07/react-v15.5.0.html#migrating-from-react.createclass : 

```
import React, { Component } from 'react';

class App extends Component {
  static contextTypes = {
        .....
  };
  static propTypes = {
        .....
  };
  render() {
    return (
      <div>
               ....
      </div>
    );
  }
  componentDidMount(){
    const { params, location, actions } = this.props;
  }
}
export default App;
```
Can you please guide me what should I do to remove these warnings ? I don't want use 'create-react-class' which is drop-in-replacement. I want to stick to the pattern of ES6 class in my existing React ver 15.6.2 without upgrading to React 16. So Can you please enlight some approaches I should follow on this ?
